/*
 * ============================================================
 * 1878. Get Biggest Three Rhombus Sums in a Grid
 * Difficulty: Medium
 * ============================================================
 *
 * PROBLEM:
 * --------
 * You are given an m x n integer matrix grid.
 *
 * A rhombus sum is the sum of the elements that form the
 * BORDER of a regular rhombus shape in the grid.
 *
 * The rhombus must have the shape of a square rotated 45°
 * with each of the corners centered in a grid cell.
 *
 * Note: rhombus can have area 0 (just a single cell) ← very important!
 *
 * Return the biggest THREE DISTINCT rhombus sums in DESCENDING order.
 * If there are less than 3 distinct values, return all of them.
 *
 * ============================================================
 * EXAMPLES:
 * ============================================================
 *
 * Example 1:
 * ----------
 * Input:
 *   grid = [[3,4,5,1,3],
 *           [3,3,4,2,3],
 *           [20,30,200,40,10],
 *           [1,5,5,4,1],
 *           [4,3,2,2,5]]
 *
 * Output: [228, 216, 211]
 *
 * Why?
 *   Blue  → center(2,1) size1: 20 + 3  + 200 + 5  = 228
 *   Red   → center(2,3) size1: 200 + 2 + 10  + 4  = 216
 *   Green → center(3,2) size1: 200 + 5 + 4   + 2  = 211
 *
 * Visually (size 1 rhombus at center row2,col1):
 *
 *              (1,1)=3          ← TOP
 *             /       \
 *      (2,0)=20       (2,2)=200 ← LEFT and RIGHT
 *             \       /
 *              (3,1)=5          ← BOTTOM
 *
 *   Sum = 3 + 200 + 5 + 20 = 228 ✅
 *
 * -------------------------------------------------------
 * Example 2:
 * ----------
 * Input:
 *   grid = [[1,2,3],
 *           [4,5,6],
 *           [7,8,9]]
 *
 * Output: [20, 9, 8]
 *
 * Why?
 *   Blue  → center(1,1) size1: 4 + 2 + 6 + 8 = 20
 *   Red   → center(2,2) size0: just cell 9
 *   Green → center(2,1) size0: just cell 8
 *
 * -------------------------------------------------------
 * Example 3:
 * ----------
 * Input:  grid = [[7,7,7]]
 * Output: [7]
 *
 * Why?
 *   All cells are 7. All rhombuses (size 0 only, tiny grid)
 *   give sum = 7. TreeSet deduplicates → only one distinct value.
 *
 * ============================================================
 * CONSTRAINTS:
 * ============================================================
 *   m == grid.length
 *   n == grid[i].length
 *   1 <= m, n <= 50
 *   1 <= grid[i][j] <= 10^5
 *
 * ============================================================
 * APPROACH (think this before coding!):
 * ============================================================
 *
 * A rhombus is defined by TWO things:
 *   1. CENTER cell (i, j)
 *   2. SIZE s (how many steps from center to each corner)
 *
 * So our plan is:
 *   → Try EVERY cell as center         (nested i, j loops)
 *   → Try EVERY possible size          (inner s loop)
 *   → Calculate border sum each time   (getRhombusSum helper)
 *   → Keep track of top 3 distinct     (TreeSet of size 3)
 *
 * Size 0 rhombus = just the center cell (always valid!)
 *
 *   size 0:      size 1:      size 2:
 *                   *             *
 *     *           * * *         *   *
 *                   *          *     *
 *                               *   *
 *                                 *
 *
 * For a rhombus of size s, the 4 corners are:
 *   TOP    = (i-s, j)
 *   RIGHT  = (i,   j+s)
 *   BOTTOM = (i+s, j)
 *   LEFT   = (i,   j-s)
 *
 * We walk the border in 4 legs (like an ant walking around the diamond):
 *   Leg 1: TOP    → RIGHT   (go down-right)
 *   Leg 2: RIGHT  → BOTTOM  (go down-left)
 *   Leg 3: BOTTOM → LEFT    (go up-left)
 *   Leg 4: LEFT   → TOP     (go up-right)
 *
 * Each leg: start AT own corner, stop BEFORE next corner
 *           → loop k = 0 to k < s   (not k <= s!)
 *           → this prevents counting corners twice
 *
 * TIME COMPLEXITY:  O(m * n * min(m,n)^2)  → fine for 50x50 grid
 * SPACE COMPLEXITY: O(1) extra (TreeSet holds at most 4 elements)
 *
 * ============================================================
 */

import java.util.TreeSet;

class Solution {

    public int[] getBiggestThree(int[][] grid) {

        int rows = grid.length;       // total number of rows
        int cols = grid[0].length;    // total number of columns

        // TreeSet = smart scoreboard that:
        //   ✅ auto-sorts values (smallest → largest internally)
        //   ✅ ignores duplicates automatically
        //   ✅ lets us remove the smallest easily (pollFirst)
        // We keep at most 3 values here at any time
        TreeSet<Integer> top3 = new TreeSet<>();

        // -------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 1: Try every cell as the center of a rhombus
        // -------------------------------------------------------
        for (int i = 0; i < rows; i++) {
            for (int j = 0; j < cols; j++) {

                // -----------------------------------------------
                // STEP 2: Find maxSize — biggest rhombus that fits
                //
                // Rhombus of size s needs:
                //   s steps UP    → need i >= s         → can go up    (i)     steps
                //   s steps DOWN  → need i+s <= rows-1  → can go down  (rows-1-i) steps
                //   s steps LEFT  → need j >= s         → can go left  (j)     steps
                //   s steps RIGHT → need j+s <= cols-1  → can go right (cols-1-j) steps
                //
                // All 4 must be satisfied → take the MINIMUM
                //
                // Example: center=(2,1), rows=5, cols=5
                //   up    = 2  (i = 2)
                //   down  = 2  (rows-1-i = 4-2 = 2)
                //   left  = 1  (j = 1)
                //   right = 3  (cols-1-j = 4-1 = 3)
                //   maxSize = min(2, 2, 1, 3) = 1 ← left side limits us!
                // -----------------------------------------------
                int maxSize = Math.min(
                                Math.min(i, rows - 1 - i),    // up vs down
                                Math.min(j, cols - 1 - j)     // left vs right
                              );

                // -----------------------------------------------
                // STEP 3: Try every size from 0 up to maxSize
                //
                // s=0 → single cell (always valid, even on edges)
                // s=1 → small 4-cell diamond
                // s=2 → bigger 8-cell diamond
                // ...
                // -----------------------------------------------
                for (int s = 0; s <= maxSize; s++) {

                    int sum = getRhombusSum(grid, i, j, s);

                    // Put this sum on the scoreboard
                    top3.add(sum);

                    // Scoreboard only holds 3 spots.
                    // If we now have 4, kick out the smallest.
                    // pollFirst() = remove the minimum from TreeSet
                    if (top3.size() > 3) {
                        top3.pollFirst();
                    }
                }
            }
        }

        // -------------------------------------------------------
        // STEP 4: Convert top3 to int array in DESCENDING order
        //
        // TreeSet internally stores: {211, 216, 228}  (ascending)
        // We want output:            [228, 216, 211]  (descending)
        // descendingSet() gives us the reverse view
        // -------------------------------------------------------
        int[] result = new int[top3.size()];
        int idx = 0;
        for (int val : top3.descendingSet()) {
            result[idx++] = val;
        }

        return result;
        // Example 1 output: [228, 216, 211] ✅
        // Example 2 output: [20, 9, 8]      ✅
        // Example 3 output: [7]             ✅
    }


    // ===========================================================
    // HELPER: Calculate border sum of rhombus at center(i,j)
    //         with given size s
    //
    // Visual of a size-2 rhombus at center (i,j):
    //
    //                  TOP
    //                (i-s, j)
    //               /        \
    //         (i-1,j-1)    (i-1,j+1)
    //            /                  \
    //    LEFT                           RIGHT
    //  (i, j-s)          *           (i, j+s)
    //            \                  /
    //         (i+1,j-1)    (i+1,j+1)
    //               \        /
    //                BOTTOM
    //               (i+s, j)
    //
    // We walk the border like an ant going clockwise:
    //   Leg1: TOP → RIGHT   (down-right direction)
    //   Leg2: RIGHT → BOTTOM (down-left direction)
    //   Leg3: BOTTOM → LEFT  (up-left direction)
    //   Leg4: LEFT → TOP     (up-right direction)
    //
    // KEY RULE: each leg starts AT its own corner
    //           but stops just BEFORE the next corner
    //           → loop k goes from 0 to k < s (NOT k <= s)
    //           → this way no corner is ever counted twice!
    // ===========================================================
    private int getRhombusSum(int[][] grid, int i, int j, int s) {

        // Size 0 = just the single center cell, no border to walk
        if (s == 0) return grid[i][j];

        int sum = 0;

        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        // LEG 1: TOP corner → towards RIGHT corner
        //        Direction: down-right (row++, col++)
        //
        //        Formula: grid[i - s + k][j + k]
        //
        //        When k=0:   grid[i-s][j]     ← TOP corner itself
        //        When k=1:   one step down-right
        //        When k=s-1: one step before RIGHT corner
        //        (RIGHT corner is picked up by Leg 2)
        //
        //        Trace: center=(2,1), s=1
        //          k=0: grid[2-1+0][1+0] = grid[1][1] = 3 ✅ (TOP)
        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        for (int k = 0; k < s; k++) {
            sum += grid[i - s + k][j + k];
        }

        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        // LEG 2: RIGHT corner → towards BOTTOM corner
        //        Direction: down-left (row++, col--)
        //
        //        Formula: grid[i + k][j + s - k]
        //
        //        When k=0:   grid[i][j+s]     ← RIGHT corner itself
        //        When k=s-1: one step before BOTTOM corner
        //
        //        Trace: center=(2,1), s=1
        //          k=0: grid[2+0][1+1-0] = grid[2][2] = 200 ✅ (RIGHT)
        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        for (int k = 0; k < s; k++) {
            sum += grid[i + k][j + s - k];
        }

        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        // LEG 3: BOTTOM corner → towards LEFT corner
        //        Direction: up-left (row--, col--)
        //
        //        Formula: grid[i + s - k][j - k]
        //
        //        When k=0:   grid[i+s][j]     ← BOTTOM corner itself
        //        When k=s-1: one step before LEFT corner
        //
        //        Trace: center=(2,1), s=1
        //          k=0: grid[2+1-0][1-0] = grid[3][1] = 5 ✅ (BOTTOM)
        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        for (int k = 0; k < s; k++) {
            sum += grid[i + s - k][j - k];
        }

        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        // LEG 4: LEFT corner → towards TOP corner
        //        Direction: up-right (row--, col++)
        //
        //        Formula: grid[i - k][j - s + k]
        //
        //        When k=0:   grid[i][j-s]     ← LEFT corner itself
        //        When k=s-1: one step before TOP corner
        //                    (TOP corner already counted in Leg 1!)
        //
        //        Trace: center=(2,1), s=1
        //          k=0: grid[2-0][1-1+0] = grid[2][0] = 20 ✅ (LEFT)
        // -----------------------------------------------------------
        for (int k = 0; k < s; k++) {
            sum += grid[i - k][j - s + k];
        }

        // Final proof for center=(2,1), s=1:
        // Leg1 + Leg2 + Leg3 + Leg4
        //  = 3  + 200  +  5  +  20  = 228 🎉 (Blue rhombus!)

        return sum;
    }
}
```

---

## The 3 Things To Never Forget
```
1. maxSize  →  min(up, down, left, right) from center
              stops the rhombus falling off the grid

2. k < s    →  each leg starts AT its corner
              stops BEFORE next corner
              → no double counting ever happens

3. TreeSet  →  add() sorts automatically + deduplicates
              pollFirst() evicts smallest when size > 3
              descendingSet() gives final answer order